qas.question: What is the Prime Minister of the UK's official residence?
Who first dubbed the British Parliament the "Mother of Parliaments?"
How many Members of Parliament are from London?
As of May 2015, which party holds the majority of seats in Parliament?
As of May 2015, how many Liberal Democrats sit in Parliament?

context: London is the seat of the Government of the United Kingdom. Many government departments are based close to the Palace of Westminster, particularly along Whitehall, including the Prime Minister's residence at <a0_0>10 Downing Street<a0_0/>. The British Parliament is often referred to as the "Mother of Parliaments" (although this sobriquet was first applied to England itself by <a1_0>John Bright<a1_0/>) because it has been the model for most other parliamentary systems. There are <a2_0>73<a2_0/> Members of Parliament (MPs) from London, who correspond to local parliamentary constituencies in the national Parliament. As of May 2015, 45 are from <a3_0>the Labour Party<a3_0/>, 27 are Conservatives, and <a4_0>one<a4_0/> is a Liberal Democrat.
